(4: Conclusions) 63 407.02 T
1 10 Q
(The paradigms discussed in this paper all, to some extent, succeed in allowing a user to 'directly' manipulate a virtual) 81 384.36 T
-0.45 (surface.  From the point of view of control, the grabbing paradigm is, at this stage of development, the preferable paradigm.) 63 373.36 P
-0.19 (From the point of view of intuitive power, the kneading paradigm is very attractive.  The kneading paradigm suffers, how-) 63 362.36 P
-0.17 (ever, from severe problems of control due to fatigue.  The pushing paradigm is somewhat of a compromise, but it does not) 63 351.36 P
(have the control of the grabbing paradigm.) 63 340.36 T
0.23 (There are times, however, when each of these paradigms is appropriate.  A system that allows the quick selection of) 81 329.36 P
(paradigms has proven to be very nice.   Further development of all three paradigms is, in our opinion, clearly warranted.) 63 318.36 T
0.34 (There are several areas where the interface to the specification of the weight function described in this paper can be) 81 307.36 P
0.24 (extended.  The system described above is built on the concept of a mask on the surface.  The bump function was used to) 63 296.36 P
-0.27 (define this mask because the bump is relatively easy to specify, as it is defined in terms of three parameters.  As mentioned) 63 285.36 P
0.43 (previ) 63 274.36 P
0.43 (ously, the concept of the mask on the surface can be generalized beyond the bump function.  This would allow the) 83.54 274.36 P
-0.35 (specification of arbitrary neighborhoods to be manipulated.  Generalizing the bump function in this way introduces no new) 63 263.36 P
(conceptual structure, but would involve considerable development of the user interface.) 63 252.36 T
